## Dependency Details & Best Practices

### ⚛️ React — `^18.3.1`

React 18.3 is the **bridge release** before React 19. It is functionally identical to 18.2 but adds deprecation warnings for APIs that will break in React 19.

**Best practices at this version:**
- Run the app and fix **all deprecation warnings** in the console — each one signals a React 19 breaking change.
- Use `createRoot()` (already in use via `main.jsx`) — `ReactDOM.render()` is removed in React 19.
- Avoid `forwardRef` where possible — React 19 passes refs as regular props.
- Avoid string refs — use `useRef` or callback refs exclusively.
- When ready to upgrade to React 19, run the official codemod: `npx codemod@latest react/19/migration-recipe`.

**React 19 new features to plan for:**
- `use()` hook for promises and context
- `useActionState` (replaces `useFormState`)
- React Compiler (automatic memoization — eliminates manual `useMemo`/`useCallback`)

---

### ⚡ Vite — `^6.4.2`

The project uses Vite 6 with the SWC plugin (`@vitejs/plugin-react-swc ^3.11.0`) for fast JSX transpilation.

**Best practices at this version:**
- Vite 6 requires Node.js 18.20+ or 20+. Ensure your environment matches.
- Uses **Environment Variables** via `import.meta.env` for client-side secrets (prefixed with `VITE_`).
- Keep using the `@/` path alias configured in `vite.config.js` — it improves import readability.
- Use `vite preview` to test production builds locally before deploying.
- Vite 6 has improved support for recursive glob imports and better HMR performance.

---

### 🧭 React Router — `^7.14.0`

React Router 7 merges the Remix framework into the React Router ecosystem, offering both SPA and full-stack modes.

**Best practices at this version:**
- This project correctly uses the **unified `react-router` package** (not `react-router-dom`) — this is the recommended approach going forward.
- Use `<NavLink>` over `<Link>` for navigation items — it provides built-in active state styling.
- Use `lazy` route property for code-splitting as the app grows.
- Nested routes + `<Outlet>` (already in use) is the correct pattern for persistent layouts.
- In v7, you can use the `data` API (loaders/actions) even in SPA mode for better data orchestration.

---

### 🎨 Tailwind CSS — `4.2.2` (v4)

Tailwind CSS v4 is a major architecture shift: **CSS-first configuration** powered by a Rust-based engine (Lightning CSS).

**Best practices at this version:**
- **No `tailwind.config.js` needed.** All configuration lives in CSS via `@theme`, `@plugin`, `@source` directives.
- Use `@theme { }` blocks to define design tokens as CSS custom properties — they automatically become Tailwind utilities.
- Plugins are loaded via `@plugin "daisyui"` in CSS (not JS config).
- Content detection is **automatic** — no need to configure `content` paths.
- Leverage native CSS features: nesting, `color-mix()`, `@layer` — the Rust engine supports them natively.
- Some utility classes were renamed from v3 (e.g., `bg-gradient-to-br` → `bg-linear-to-br`). Use `npx @tailwindcss/upgrade` if migrating old code.
- The PostCSS integration uses `@tailwindcss/postcss` (configured in `postcss.config.js`).

---

### 🌼 DaisyUI — `5.5.19`

DaisyUI 5 is designed specifically for Tailwind CSS v4, using native CSS features like `color-mix()` and CSS variables.

**Best practices at this version:**
- Install via `@plugin "daisyui"` in your CSS file (CSS-first pattern).
- Configure themes directly in CSS: `@plugin "daisyui" { themes: light --default, dark --prefersdark; }`.
- Note the theme names in DaisyUI 5 may differ slightly from 4.x for some custom palettes.
- Use DaisyUI classes for **semantic component structure** (btn, card, input, etc.) and Tailwind utilities for **layout, spacing, and typography**.

---

### 🎯 @iconify/react — `5.0.1`

Universal icon library with 200,000+ icons from 100+ icon sets, loaded on demand.

**Best practices at this version:**
- v5 uses functional components and React hooks — this is the current modern API.
- Icons load on demand — only icons actually used are fetched. Do not bundle entire icon sets.
- Prefer `className` over `style` props for styling icons (better Tailwind integration).

---

### 🔧 clsx `2.1.1` + tailwind-merge `2.4.0`

Used together in the `cn()` utility (`src/modules/core/utils/cn.js`).

**Best practices:**
- **Always use `cn()`** when combining conditional classes or accepting external `className` props in components.
- `clsx` handles conditional logic (objects, arrays, falsy values).
- `tailwind-merge` resolves conflicting Tailwind classes (e.g., `px-2 px-4` → `px-4`).

---

### 🔍 ESLint — `^9.39.4`

The project has been migrated to **ESLint 9** with the new **Flat Config** format (`eslint.config.js`).

**Best practices at this version:**
- Use `eslint.config.js` exclusively. Delete any legacy `.eslintrc.*` or `.eslintignore` files.
- Globals are now managed via the `globals` package (imported in `eslint.config.js`).
- Use `settings: { react: { version: 'detect' } }` to avoid manual versioning.
- The `ignores` key replaces `.eslintignore`.

---

### 💅 Prettier — `3.3.2`

**Plugins in use:**
- `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss` (`0.7.2`) — automatic Tailwind class sorting

**Best practices:**
- `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss` 0.7+ is compatible with Tailwind CSS v4.
- **Required:** The config includes `"tailwindStylesheet": "./src/index.css"` to allow the plugin to resolve v4 `@theme` variables and custom utilities.
- Always keep this plugin **last** in the plugins array.

---

### 🌙 theme-change — `2.5.0`

Lightweight library for toggling CSS themes (used with DaisyUI's theme system).

**Best practices:**
- Use with DaisyUI's `data-theme` attribute for theme switching.
- Ensure initialization happens in the main entry point (already handled in `ThemeContextProvider`).

---

### 🚀 gh-pages — `6.1.1`

Deploys the `dist/` folder to the `gh-pages` branch for GitHub Pages hosting.

**Best practices:**
- The `base` path in `vite.config.js` is correctly set to `/shortly/` in production — required for GitHub Pages subdirectory hosting.
- Use `pnpm run deploy` which triggers `predeploy` (build) automatically.
